WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.560
Welcome to the Qiskit in Classrooms module
on quantum key distribution.

00:00:04.560 --> 00:00:08.880
My name is Katie McCormick and today we're
going to explore how quantum mechanics

00:00:08.880 --> 00:00:13.200
can help us share encryption keys securely.

00:00:13.200 --> 00:00:17.440
First, let's talk about why we need
quantum key distribution in the first place.

00:00:17.440 --> 00:00:22.080
In classical cryptography, two parties
who want to communicate securely

00:00:22.080 --> 00:00:25.920
need to share a secret key that only
they know about.

00:00:25.920 --> 00:00:30.560
The challenge is: how do you share that
key without an eavesdropper intercepting it?

00:00:30.560 --> 00:00:35.200
This is where quantum mechanics comes in.
The BB84 protocol, developed by

00:00:35.200 --> 00:00:40.640
Charles Bennett and Gilles Brassard in 1984,
uses the properties of quantum states

00:00:40.640 --> 00:00:44.480
to detect any eavesdropping attempt.

00:00:44.480 --> 00:00:49.120
The key idea is that measuring a quantum
state disturbs it. If someone tries to

00:00:49.120 --> 00:00:53.760
intercept the quantum bits being sent
between Alice and Bob, their measurement

00:00:53.760 --> 00:00:57.600
will introduce errors that Alice and Bob
can detect.

00:00:57.600 --> 00:01:02.240
Let's walk through the protocol step by step.
Alice starts by preparing a sequence of qubits.

00:01:02.240 --> 00:01:07.680
For each qubit, she randomly chooses one of
two bases: the computational basis,

00:01:07.680 --> 00:01:12.320
which uses the states zero and one, or the
Hadamard basis, which uses plus and minus.

00:01:12.320 --> 00:01:17.760
She then randomly assigns a bit value,
zero or one, and prepares the qubit accordingly.

00:01:17.760 --> 00:01:22.400
Bob receives each qubit and measures it
in a randomly chosen basis as well.

00:01:22.400 --> 00:01:27.040
After all qubits are sent, Alice and Bob
publicly compare which bases they used,

00:01:27.040 --> 00:01:30.880
but not the results of their measurements.

00:01:30.880 --> 00:01:35.520
When they used the same basis, their
results should match perfectly.

00:01:35.520 --> 00:01:40.160
They keep only these matching-basis results
and discard the rest.

00:01:40.160 --> 00:01:44.800
This gives them a shared string of bits —
the raw key.

00:01:44.800 --> 00:01:49.440
Now here's where it gets interesting.
If an eavesdropper, Eve, tried to measure

00:01:49.440 --> 00:01:54.080
the qubits in transit, she would have had
to guess the basis for each qubit.

00:01:54.080 --> 00:01:58.720
About half the time, she'd guess wrong,
and her measurement would disturb the state.

00:01:58.720 --> 00:02:03.360
Alice and Bob can detect this by comparing
a random subset of their shared key.

00:02:03.360 --> 00:02:07.200
If they find errors, they know someone
was listening and they abort.

00:02:07.200 --> 00:02:12.640
In this module, you'll implement this
protocol using Qiskit and see it in action.

00:02:12.640 --> 00:02:17.280
You'll create the quantum circuits,
simulate the key exchange,

00:02:17.280 --> 00:02:20.480
and even test what happens when
Eve tries to eavesdrop.

00:02:20.480 --> 00:02:24.000
Let's get started!
